@startuml brain_maturation
!theme plain
skinparam backgroundColor #FEFEFE
skinparam defaultFontSize 12
skinparam titleFontSize 18

title Neuroscience Basis: Why 0–35?\nPrefrontal Cortex Maturation & Parenting Strategy

map "Age 0–5" as a1 {
  Brain => Amygdala, limbic, sensory cortex
  Male PFC => Forming
  Female PFC => Forming
  Parenting => Safety, attachment, modeling
}

map "Age 6–12" as a2 {
  Brain => Temporal/parietal specialization
  Male PFC => Pruning
  Female PFC => Pruning
  Parenting => Skill exposure, habit formation
}

map "Age 13–17" as a3 {
  Brain => Limbic system dominates
  Male PFC => Immature
  Female PFC => Approaching maturity
  Parenting => Firm boundaries, explain consequences
}

map "Age 18–21" as a4 {
  Brain => PFC gaining ground
  Male PFC => Still developing
  Female PFC => Nearing completion
  Parenting => Release control gradually
}

map "Age 21–24" as a5 {
  Brain => PFC integration accelerates
  Male PFC => Still developing
  Female PFC => **MATURE**
  Parenting => Female: peer relationship
}

map "Age 25–30" as a6 {
  Brain => Full myelination completing
  Male PFC => **MATURE**
  Female PFC => Mature
  Parenting => Male: peer relationship
}

map "Age 31–35" as a7 {
  Brain => Pattern recognition, wisdom circuits
  Male PFC => Fully operational
  Female PFC => Fully operational
  Parenting => Legacy transfer, mutual stewardship
}

a1 -down-> a2
a2 -down-> a3
a3 -down-> a4
a4 -down-> a5
a5 -down-> a6
a6 -down-> a7

note right of a3
  Limbic-PFC imbalance explains
  adolescent risk-taking.
  (Casey et al., 2008)
end note

note right of a5
  Female PFC matures ~21–24
  (Ingalhalikar et al., 2014, U. Penn)
end note

note right of a6
  Male PFC matures ~25–30
  (Giedd, NIH; Lebel & Beaulieu, 2011)
end note

note bottom of a7
  **Key Sources:**
  • Giedd, J.N. et al. — NIH Longitudinal Brain Imaging Study (1999–2015)
  • Lebel, C. & Beaulieu, C. (2011) — Longitudinal Development of Human Brain Wiring
  • Ingalhalikar, M. et al. (2014) — U. Penn, sex-based connectivity differences
  • Sowell, E.R. et al. (2003) — UCLA, cortical maturation through mid-20s
  • Casey, B.J. et al. (2008) — The Adolescent Brain

  **Practical Meaning:**
  A 22-year-old male may appear adult but is still neurologically
  forming executive judgment. Support through 30+.
  The 0–35 window ensures 5–10 years of mature-brain validation.
end note

@enduml
